{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"92c7dbf8-d309-4d60-a835-5614fd849c17","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_016scvikqQq7PabqcRGHWxAj","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Configuring .NET crash dumps"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01LbaZJhFHWWf8HqAtmefWvs","name":"view","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-d901cadb8e7a41ba80166abc38e7147d"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"view the file at /tmp/sv-d901cadb8e7a41ba80166abc38e7147d."}],"interactionId":"d9eebcfa-0f0e-4c88-b701-39536707e63c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to configure automatic crash dump collection for a NativeAOT .NET 11 app running in Kubernetes. They have `createdump` installed at `/opt/tools/createdump`. Let me think about what's needed:\n\n1. **Environment variables** for .NET crash dump configuration\n2. **Kubernetes pod spec changes** (volume mounts, env vars, etc.)\n\nFor .NET crash dumps with NativeAOT, the key environment variables are:\n- `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1` — enables automatic crash dump generation\n- `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType` — sets dump type (1=Mini, 2=Heap, 3=Triage, 4=Full)\n\n\n- `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName` — path/pattern for dump files\n- `DOTNET_CreateDumpDiagnostics` — enables diagnostics for the dump process\n- `DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath` — points to the createdump tool, which is essential for NativeAOT since it doesn't bundle the tool itself\n\nNow I need to think through the actual Kubernetes configuration. The main pieces are setting those environment variables, creating storage for the dumps, and making sure the directory is writable when the container starts.","outputTokens":545,"requestId":"D7C1:11B452:104C3FA:12A0386:69F2B546"},"id":"288ca605-008f-4e62-8a0b-4f63aaa200db","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:50:11.345Z","parentId":"0a46e146-a856-4adc-9c9c-12e9d4520f59"}
